The paper deals with the problem of estimating an integer vector from linear observations corrupted by noise, which is a common problem in information theory and communication systems. The paper specifically focuses on the analysis of successive interference cancellation (SIC) decoders, which are widely used in digital communications due to their low complexity. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also deals with communication systems and their performance analysis, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.COMM (Communication and Networking). The use of SIC decoders involves processing large amounts of data, which could also place the paper in the sub-categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper deals with the problem of estimating an integer vector, which could also place it in the sub-category of cs.NI (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
